abstract = {It is known in the current scientific literature that people living on the autism spectrum have a lower quality of sleep compared to neurotypical people, and the internal factors for this have already been well established. In focus groups with experts, it was pointed out that environmental factors (street noise, light sources, air quality, temperature, Vibrations) could also have a significant impact on sleep quality. A semi-structured literature search on assistive technology to cope with these issues revealed no relevant literature on this topic at the time of the investigation. A concept was set up in an iterative process based on the current literature. This concept includes a developed study design and three components: a sensor system for recording the environmental factors, and already existing technology (Withings Sleep Analyzer) for the contactless recording of physiological sleep data and a questionnaire to measure internal sleep-influencing factors. The results of this study will be used to develop appropriate sensor technology to collect and analyze sleep data, compare it with environmental factors, detect sleep-influencing factors and finally support caregivers and people living in the autism spectrum themselves.},
